{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"14dae903-21b3-40e8-afcb-783fb35a6e74","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads that are already at the expected version but have become corrupted or partially installed. It doesn't fetch newer versions.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, `update` is the right fix:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, try `dotnet workload repair` as a follow-up in case any files got into a bad state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b3a1ba64-1697-41a8-ad49-d8dff35af055","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"1040:2A621F:147A72A:170F0AB:69FD3380"},"id":"c23197d9-0db5-4580-a66c-0fee0ea95192","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:51:20.511Z","parentId":"7b994408-e458-4867-8bfa-0a296f85d79a"}
